                "name": "Isabella Morris",
                "href": "/profile/Isabella-Morris-9"
            },
            "answer_text": "This question is hard to answer without knowing what your argument is! I would explain my argument in my introduction as though I was talking to a tutor in a tutorial or class setting, then apply a bit of polish afterwards. Honestly, I think \u201cIn this essay, I shall discuss\u201d is fine, as long as you keep the personal pronouns to a minimum otherwise. This is true especially if you\u2019re detailing HOW you\u2019re planning to answer the question (using a particular theory or methodology) as well as WHAT you\u2019re answering it with. Maybe look at what the prevailing wisdom about your topic is - do academics say X, but you think the right answer is X AND something, BUT something or DESPITE something? Make that clear. Maybe mention which author you most agree with, and summarise why. And what does it mean, if your answer is right? How should we change the way we study the topic, or evaluate an idea? This can also finish a strong introduction. ",
